key "lectureUZ"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000

\series bold
Decision
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

maker
\series default
: The decision maker is the one who is responsible for the consequences
 of their decisions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000

\series bold
Goal
\series default
: The desired state of our decision problem, usually it is what we want
 to achieve after solving the decision problem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000

\series bold
Initial
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

state
\series default
: The beginning state of our decision problem i.e.
 all the measurements, parameters, conditions or factors we have before
 starting the decision-making process.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000

\series bold
Alternatives
\series default
: The options or alternative courses of action which are the possibilities
 of realizing our goal or desired state.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000

\series bold
Criterion
\series default
: A measurement or a standard which allows comparing between different options
 or alternatives.
 For example, when we want to buy a new house, measurements such as the
 number of rooms, the number of floors, or the price of the house can be
 used to compare between alternatives.
 Also, a criterion can also be known as a measurable index, a measurable
 attribute or a measurable characteristic.
 A criterion can also be positive or negative, for example, criteria related
 to time such as time to manufacture, time to delivery or response time
 are negative criteria because for these criteria we often want their values
 as small as possible.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000

\series bold
Constraints
\series default
: Limitations stated by the decision problem.
 For example, a budget to buy a new house can not exceed 50.000 US dollars
 or the response time from a computer system should be below 100 milliseconds.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000

\series bold
Consequences
\series default
: Outcomes or results we get after realizing the goal with the option or
 alternative we have chosen.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000

\series bold
Uncertainty
\series default
: In a decision situation, uncertainty is an unknown factor that could affect
 the outcomes of the decision situation.
 For example, when we are traveling, going by plane is a good decision since
 it is fast and cheap for a long trip, but we can not know if we are going
 to be captured by terrorist or not.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000

\series bold
Preferences
\series default
: The view of the decision maker which determines what kind of criterion
 the decision maker will use in the decision situation.
 For example, when choosing a house to buy, if the decision maker only prefers
 the appearance of the house then he may choose criteria such as the number
 of windows, the color of the wall, or what kind of architectural style
 the house is.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000

\series bold
Decision-making
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

process
\series default
: The process in which the decision maker makes the evaluation of alternatives
 with respect to criteria and constraints.
 The result of this process is the final suggestion to the decision maker
 so he or she can make the final decision.
\end_layout

