\begin_layout Subsection
The necessity of Decision Analysis
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Why-people-use"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In sections 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:The-foundation-of"

\end_inset

-
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:The-process-of"

\end_inset

, we learned that in a decision-making process, the decision maker has the
 responsibility to choose the right decision in order to realize the goal
 in that particular situation.
 However, there are many factors with hidden information in a decision-making
 process that can hide the true value of each decision thus affect the judgment
 of the decision maker.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, consider the situation when we choose suppliers for providing
 materials to build a particular product.
 If we do not spend the time to research the past performance of each supplier,
 we will never know the true value of each supplier in terms of providing
 the needed materials.
 Thus our judgment for choosing the suppliers will not be certain.
 To overcome this difficulty of uncertain judgment, a decision maker will
 need to practice Decision Analysis in a decision-making process.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Decision Analysis or Decision Aiding (DA) can be defined as follows 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "roy2005paradigms"

\end_inset

: DA is an activity in which the decision maker uses explicit and formalized
 models to obtain more information in a decision process.
 In other words, it is the process of getting more information from the
 decision problem in order to clarify various elements inside the decision
 situation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With the above definition, DA's purpose is to establish the decision-making
 process in a scientifically based way to clear out the uncertainty in the
 decision maker's judgment 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "roy2005paradigms"

\end_inset

.
 It is made possible by providing the decision-making process with working
 hypotheses and formulations of propositions such as satisfying solutions
 or possible compromises.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "subsec:From-Monocriteria-to"

\end_inset

, we will present to readers the notions of Mono-criterion approach and
 Multi-criteria approach, thus the reason why Multi-criteria approach is
 the preferred tool for many decision makers in decision analysis.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
From Mono-criterion to Multi-criteria
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:From-Monocriteria-to"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In a decision-making process, a decision maker has two approaches to evaluate
 the options.
 They are Mono-criterion approach and Multi-criteria approach.
 To simply put, Mono-criterion approach is when the decision maker only
 uses one criterion for determining the value of each option of the decision
 problem.
 Multi-criteria approach, on the other hand, evaluates each option on many
 different criteria associated with various aspects of the decision problem.
 Readers can find more information about criterion in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "subsec:Basic-concept-mcda"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When a decision maker is dealing with a DA process, it is very difficult
 for the decision maker to think with only one single criterion in his or
 her mind only (Mono-criterion approach).
 In a multi-actor environment, it is even more unlikely for that single
 criterion to satisfy the point of view of every actor in the decision-making
 process because each actor plays a different role in that process which
 gives different preference to the actor own objectives and value system
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "roy2005paradigms"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For any case, it is essential to consider every point of view dealing with
 many perspectives of a decision-making process, for example, the financial
 status, the current human resources, the affected ecosystem, security or
 quality of services.
 By regarding each related point of view individually, independently from
 the others, it is likely to arrive at a clear decision that meets all actors'
 preferences and requirements 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "roy2005paradigms"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore, it is typical to associating a particular criterion to each related
 point of view (Multi-criteria approach) and use a suitable scale (qualitative
 scale or quantitative scale) to evaluate any potential action 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "roy2005paradigms"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As we can see, in many decision-making contexts, using Mono-criterion approach
 might overlook certain aspects of the decision problem, thus affecting
 the judgment of the decision maker.
 Using Multi-criteria approach in such cases will help the decision maker
 to avoid the aforementioned danger of neglecting.
\end_layout

